   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                              target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">King Lear</ref></title></hi>].
                        <note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"><title><title><ref
                                    target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">King Lear</ref></title>;
                              A Tragedy, In Five Acts; By <ref
                                 target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William Shakspeare</ref>.
                              As Performed at the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref> and <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>. Printed
                              Under the Authority of the Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks
                              by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                           Inchbald</ref></title></hi>, London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees,
                        and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-6. <hi rendition="#italics"><title
                              level="m">The British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays, Which Are
                              Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury
                                 Lane</ref>, <ref target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent
                                 Garden</ref>, and <ref target="people.html#Haymarket"
                                 >Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the Authority of the Managers from
                              the Prompt Books. With Biographical and Critical Remarks, by <ref
                                 target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs. Inchbald.</ref></title></hi>
                        In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. IV. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">King
                        Lear</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#Cunobelinus">Cymbeline</ref></title></hi>. <hi
                           rendition="#italics"><title><ref target="people.html#Macbeth"
                                 >Macbeth</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#CaesarJulius">Julius Cæsar</ref></title></hi>.
                           <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref target="people.html#AntoniusMarcus"
                                 >Antony</ref> and <ref
                                 target="people.html#CleopatraVIIQueenofEgypt"
                              >Cleopatra</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst,
                        Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play
                        was staged at the Globe Theatre in late 1605 or early 1606. Laura DeWitt and
                        Mary A. Waters edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics">The Criticism
                           Archive</hi>. </note>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p>The story of this Tragedy has been told in many an ancient ballad, and other
               ingenious works; but <ref target="people.html#MaloneEdmond">Mr. Malone</ref>
               supposes, that <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref> is more
               indebted for his fable to "<title>The true Chronicle History of <ref
                     target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">King Lear</ref> and his three Daughters,
                  Goneril, Regan, and Cordelia,</title>"<note>From <ref
                     target="people.html#MaloneEdmond">Edmond Malone</ref>'s <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Plays and Poems of <ref
                           target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William
                     Shakspeare</ref></title></hi>, vol. 8, p. 485. The play to which <ref
                     target="people.html#MaloneEdmond">Edmond</ref> refers was anonymously published
                  roughly twelve years prior to the first staging of <hi rendition="#italics"
                           ><title><ref target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">King
                        Lear</ref></title></hi> and is believed to be <ref
                     target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakespeare</ref>'s primary
                  inspiration. Goneril, Regan, and Cordelia are <ref
                     target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">King Lear</ref>'s eldest, second, and
                  youngest daughters, respectively. While Goneril and Regan are the play's villains,
                  deceiving their father with false flattery to accrue power, Cordelia refuses to
                  make false professions of love, and her father banishes her from his
                  kingdom.</note> than to any other production.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#CamdenWilliam">Camden</ref>, in his <title>Remains</title>,
               gives the following account of an English King, which is also similar to the story of
                  <ref target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">Leir</ref>, or <ref
                  target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">Lear</ref>. <quote><ref
                     target="people.html#IneKingofWessex">Ina</ref>, King of the West Saxons, had
                  three daughters, of whom, upon a time, he demanded, whether they did love him, and
                  so would do during their lives, above all others? The two elder sware deeply they
                  would; the youngest, but the wisest, told her father flatly, that albeit she did
                  love, honour, and reverence him, and so would whilst she lived, as much as nature
                  and daughterly duty at the uttermost could expect; yet she did think that one day
                  it would come to pass, that she should affect another more fervently, meaning her
                  husband, when she were married.<note>From <ref target="people.html#CamdenWilliam"
                        >William Camden</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Remaines of a
                           Greater Worke, Concerning Britaine, the Inhabitants Thereof, Their
                           Languages, Names, Surnames, Empreses, Wise Speeches, Poësies, and
                           Epitaphes</title></hi> (1605), p. 182.</note></quote></p>

            <p>This relation, the Commentator imagines, may probably have been applied to <ref
                  target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">King Lear</ref>; whom <ref
                  target="people.html#GeoffryofMonmouth">Geoffrey of Monmouth</ref> says, "Nobly
               governed his country for sixty years, and died about eight hundred years before the
               birth of Christ."<note>From <ref target="people.html#GeoffryofMonmouth">Geoffrey of
                     Monmouth</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Historia Regum
                        Britanniae</title></hi> (<hi rendition="#italics"><title>The History of the
                        Kings of Britain</title></hi>) (c. 1136), Book II, Chapter XI, p. 45.</note>
            </p>

            <p>Notwithstanding the number of histories and books of fiction, that have promulgated
               this piteous tale of a monarch and his children, it remains a doubt <fw type="sig"
                     ><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw><pb n="4"/>among the most learned on the
               subject, whether such an event, as here described, ever, in reality,
                     occurred.<note><hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                           target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">King Lear</ref></title></hi> is
                  based on the mythological <ref target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">Leir of
                     Britain</ref>. The story of <ref target="people.html#LearKingofBritain"
                     >Leir</ref> was first documented in <ref target="people.html#GeoffryofMonmouth"
                     >Geoffrey of Monmouth</ref>'s twelfth-century pseudohistory, <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>Historia Regum Britanniae</title></hi> (<hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The History of the Kings of Britain</title></hi>),
                  which claimed <ref target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">Leir</ref> ruled in the
                  eighth century B.C.E. However, no account of <ref
                     target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">Leir</ref> is recognized as verifiable
                  history.</note></p>

            <p>But, if it never did before the time of <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam"
                  >Shakspeare</ref>, certainly something very like it has taken place since. <ref
                  target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">Lear</ref> is not represented much more
               affectionate to his daughters by <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam"
                  >Shakspeare</ref>, than <ref target="people.html#JamesIIKingofEngland">James the
                  Second</ref> is by <ref target="people.html#HumeDavid">Hume</ref>. <ref
                  target="people.html#JamesIIKingofEngland">James</ref>'s daughters were, besides,
               under more than ordinary obligations to their king and father, for the tenderness he
               had evinced towards their mother, in raising her from an humble station to the
               elevation of his own; and thus preserving these two princesses from the probable
               disgrace of illegitimate birth.<note><ref target="people.html#JamesIIKingofEngland"
                     >James II</ref> promised commoner <ref target="people.html#HydeAnne">Anne
                     Hyde</ref> he would marry her as he attempted to seduce her in 1659. <ref
                     target="people.html#HydeAnne">Hyde</ref> became pregnant out of wedlock, and
                  the following year, the couple married in secret.</note></p>

            <p>Even to such persons as hold it was right to drive <ref
                  target="people.html#JamesIIKingofEngland">King James</ref> from the throne, it
               must be a subject of lamentation, that his beloved children were the chief
               instruments of those concerned. When the <ref
                  target="people.html#JamesIIKingofEngland">King</ref> was informed that his eldest
               daughter, <ref target="people.html#MaryIIQueenofEngland">Mary</ref>, was landed, and
               proceeding to the metropolis, in order to dethrone him, he called, as the historian
               relates, for the <ref target="people.html#AnneQueenofGreatBritain">Princess
                  Anne</ref>&#8212;and called for her by the tender description of his "dear, his
               only remaining daughter." On the information given to his Majesty in return, that
               "she had forsook the palace, to join her sister," the king wept and tore his
                  hair.<note>Altered quotation from <ref target="people.html#HumeDavid">David
                     Hume</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The History of Great
                        Britain</title></hi> (1757), vol. II, p. 423. In 1688, <ref
                     target="people.html#MaryIIQueenofEngland">Princess Mary</ref>'s husband, <ref
                     target="people.html#WilliamIIIKingofEngland">William of Orange</ref>, led the
                  forces which deposed <ref target="people.html#JamesIIKingofEngland">James II</ref>
                  in the Glorious Revolution. Upon <ref target="people.html#WilliamIIIKingofEngland"
                     >William</ref>'s arrival, many of <ref
                     target="people.html#JamesIIKingofEngland">James</ref>' Protestant supporters,
                  including his daughter, <ref target="people.html#AnneQueenofGreatBritain"
                     >Anne</ref>, defected to join William. However, <ref
                     target="people.html#MaryIIQueenofEngland">Mary</ref> did not arrive until two
                  months after her father's departure.</note></p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">Lear</ref>, exposed on a bleak heath,
               suffered not more than <ref target="people.html#JamesIIKingofEngland">James</ref>, at
               one of our sea-ports, trying to escape to France. <ref
                  target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">King Lear</ref> was only pelted by a storm,
                  <ref target="people.html#JamesIIKingofEngland">King James</ref> by his merciless
                  subjects.<note>In Act II, scene iv, <ref target="people.html#LearKingofBritain"
                     >King Lear</ref> tries to take refuge with Goneril and Regan, who turn him out
                  in a storm. However, <ref target="people.html#JamesIIKingofEngland">James</ref>
                  made his escape in the middle of the night, in secret, making it unlikely he would
                  have faced attacks by his subjects.</note></p>

            <p>Not one of <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref>'s plays more
               violently agitates the passions than this Tragedy; parents and <pb n="5"/>children
               are alike interested in every character, and instructed by each. There is,
               nevertheless, too much of ancient cruelty in many of the events. An audience finds
               horror prevail over compassion, on Gloster's loss of his eyes:<note>Cornwall, the
                  son-in-law of the king, gouges out the eyes of the Earl of Gloucester, a nobleman
                  loyal to <ref target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">King Lear</ref>, in Act III,
                  scene vii.</note> and though <ref target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Dr.
                  Johnson</ref> has vindicated this frightful incident, by saying, "<ref
                  target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref> well knew what would
               please the audience for which he wrote;"<note>From <hi rendition="#italics"
                        ><title>The Plays of <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William
                           Shakespeare</ref>, With the Corrections and Illustrations of Various
                        Commentators</title></hi> (1765), vol. 6, p. 159.</note> yet this argument
               is no apology for the correctors of <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam"
                  >Shakspeare</ref>, who have altered the Drama to gratify spectators more refined,
               and yet have not expunged this savage and improbable act.</p>

            <p>The nice distinction which the author has made between the real and the counterfeit
               madman in this tragedy, is a part of the work particularly admired by the experienced
               observers of that fatal disorder; and to sum up the whole worth of the production,
               the reader may now say of it, with some degree of qualification, what <ref
                  target="people.html#TateNahum">Tate</ref> said before he had employed much time
               and taste on the alteration: "It is a heap of jewels, unstrung and unpolished, yet so
               dazzling in their disorder, that I soon perceived I had seized a treasure."<note>From
                  the "Dedication" section prefacing <ref target="people.html#TateNahum">Nahum
                     Tate</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The History of <ref
                           target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">King Lear</ref></title></hi>
                  (1681), p. 3.</note>
            </p>

            <p>It is curious and consolatory for a minor critic to observe, how the great
               commentators on <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref> differ
               in their opinions.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#TateNahum">Tate</ref> alters the Play of <title><ref
                     target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">King Lear</ref></title>, and instead of
               suffering the good Cordelia to die of grief, as <ref
                  target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref> had done, he rewards her
               with life, love, and a throne. <ref target="people.html#AddisonJoseph">Addison</ref>,
               in his <title>Spectator</title>, condemns him for this;<note>Of <ref
                     target="people.html#TateNahum">Tate</ref>'s alteration, <ref
                     target="people.html#AddisonJoseph">Joseph Addison</ref> writes, "<hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title><ref target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">King
                           Lear</ref></title></hi> is an admirable Tragedy of the same Kind, as <ref
                     target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakespear</ref> wrote it; but as it is
                  reformed according to the chymerical Notion of Poetical Justice, in my humble
                  Opinion it has lost half its Beauty." <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The
                        Spectator</title></hi> no. 40, April 16, 1711.</note>
               <ref target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Dr. Johnson</ref> commends him for
                     it;<note><ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> refers to <ref
                     target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Johnson</ref>'s comment in his 1765 work,
                     <hi rendition="#italics">The Plays of <ref
                        target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William Shakespeare</ref></hi>, vol.
                  6, p. 159. <quote>In the present case the publick has decided. Cordelia, from the
                     time of <ref target="people.html#TateNahum">Tate</ref>, has always retired with
                     victory and felicity. And, if my sensations could add any thing to the general
                     suffrage, I might relate, that I was many years ago so shocked by Cordelia's
                     death, that I know not whether I ever endured to read again the last scenes of
                     the play till I undertook to revise them as an editor.</quote></note>
               <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi></fw><pb n="6"/>both showing excellent
               reasons. Then comes <ref target="people.html#SteevensGeorge">Steevens</ref>, who
               gives a better reason than all, why they are all wrong.<note><ref
                     target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> refers to <ref
                     target="people.html#SteevensGeorge">Steevens</ref>' comment in <hi
                     rendition="#italics">The Plays of <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam"
                        >William Shakespeare</ref>, With the Corrections and Illustrations of
                     Various Commentators<title/></hi> (1793), vol. 14, p. 290.<quote>This princess,
                     according to the old historians, retired with victory from the battle she
                     conducted in her father's cause, and thereby replaced him on the throne: but in
                     a subsequent one fought against her (after the death of the old king) by the
                     sons of Goneril and Regan, she was taken, and died miserably in prison. The
                     poet found this in history, and was therefore willing to precipitate her death,
                     which he knew had happened but a few years after. The dramatick writers of this
                     age suffered as small a number of their heroes and heroines to escape as
                     possible; nor could the filial piety of this lady, any more than the innocence
                     of <ref target="people.html#Ophelia">Ophelia</ref>, prevail on <ref
                        target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref> to extend her life
                     beyond her misfortunes.</quote></note>
            </p>
